<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1437,1024,1375]" pageId="27" pageNumber="428">
With 
<typeStatus box="[216,264,1025,1051]" pageId="27" pageNumber="428">type</typeStatus>
locality referred as Tefé, Amazonas, 
<collectingCountry box="[698,766,1024,1050]" name="Brazil" pageId="27" pageNumber="428">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Sclater, P. L." box="[784,938,1024,1051]" pageId="27" pageNumber="428" pagination="128 - 133" refId="ref29937" refString="Sclater, P. L. (1858) On some new or little-known species of Accipitres, in the collection of the Norwich Museum. Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London, 1858, 128 - 133. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1469 - 7998.1858. tb 06354. x" type="journal article" year="1858">Sclater, 1858</bibRefCitation>
), and corresponding to specimens in Clade B, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sclater" baseAuthorityYear="1858" box="[185,270,1061,1086]" class="Aves" family="Strigidae" genus="Megascops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Strigiformes" pageId="27" pageNumber="428" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="usta">
<emphasis box="[185,270,1061,1086]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="428">M. usta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distributed over a wide geographic area in Amazonia, ranging from west of the Branco-Negro rivers throughout the Imerí, Napo, Inambari, Madeira and upper stretches of the Tapajos and Xingu AOEs. Strong statistical support for reciprocal monophyly, high degree of coalescence, and high uncorrected pairwise p-distances ranging from 2.1% (
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hekstra" baseAuthorityYear="1982" box="[328,409,1169,1194]" class="Aves" family="Strigidae" genus="Megascops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Strigiformes" pageId="27" pageNumber="428" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ater">
<emphasis box="[328,409,1169,1194]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="428">M. ater</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) to 6.4% (
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="ANSP" baseAuthorityYear="2445" box="[527,658,1169,1194]" class="Aves" family="Strigidae" genus="Megascops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Strigiformes" pageId="27" pageNumber="428" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="watsonii">
<emphasis box="[527,658,1169,1194]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="428">M. watsonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) differentiates this taxon from others in the 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="428">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dantas &amp; Weckstein &amp; Bates &amp; Oliveira &amp; Catanach &amp; Aleixo" authorityYear="2021" box="[1146,1272,1169,1194]" class="Aves" family="Strigidae" genus="Megascops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Strigiformes" pageId="27" pageNumber="428" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Megascops</taxonomicName>
atricapilla-M. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="ANSP" baseAuthorityYear="2445" box="[151,246,1205,1230]" class="Aves" family="Strigidae" genus="Megascops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Strigiformes" pageId="27" pageNumber="428" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="watsonii">watsonii</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
complex. Morphologically variable with multiple morphs, mainly brown or red, but also gray, and not safely distinguishable solely based on morphology from the other species in the complex. There is geographical variation in the frequency of different morphs among populations. Apparently does not include morphs as dark in color as those found in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="ANSP" baseAuthorityYear="2445" box="[416,548,1313,1338]" class="Aves" family="Strigidae" genus="Megascops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Strigiformes" pageId="27" pageNumber="428" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="watsonii">
<emphasis box="[416,548,1313,1338]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="428">M. watsonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hekstra" baseAuthorityYear="1982" box="[604,687,1313,1338]" class="Aves" family="Strigidae" genus="Megascops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Strigiformes" pageId="27" pageNumber="428" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ater">
<emphasis box="[604,687,1313,1338]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="428">M. ater</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Vocally distinct from 
<emphasis box="[945,1225,1313,1338]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="428">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="ANSP" baseAuthorityYear="2445" box="[945,1081,1313,1338]" class="Aves" family="Strigidae" genus="Megascops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Strigiformes" pageId="27" pageNumber="428" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="watsonii">M. watsonii</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dantas &amp; Weckstein &amp; Bates &amp; Oliveira &amp; Catanach &amp; Aleixo" authorityYear="2021" box="[1092,1225,1313,1338]" class="Aves" family="Strigidae" genus="Megascops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Strigiformes" pageId="27" pageNumber="428" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="stangiae">M. stangiae</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1822" box="[1280,1436,1312,1338]" class="Aves" family="Strigidae" genus="Megascops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Strigiformes" pageId="27" pageNumber="428" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="atricapilla">
<emphasis box="[1280,1436,1312,1338]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="428">M. atricapilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by on average slower-paced longsongs and shortsongs (
<figureCitation box="[774,842,1348,1374]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1132,1156]" captionTargetBox="[207,1378,200,1108]" captionTargetId="figure-20@15.[207,1380,200,1108]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 9. Geographic variation in longsong paces (notes/s) across clades A–F in the Megascops atricapilla-M. watsonii complex. Locality codes are given as letters followed by numbers and can be found in full in the Appendix. Numbers next to locality dots represent locally measured longsong pace values. When more than one individual was sampled at a given locality, the total number of longsongs measured is given in parentheses, with reported values representing averages." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4640348" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4640348/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="428">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
; 
<tableCitation box="[855,950,1348,1374]" captionStart="TABLE 6" captionStartId="14.[151,239,1560,1584]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="TABLE 6. Mean and standard deviation values of nine “longsong” characters measured for Megascops atricapilla-M. watsonii individuals belonging to clades A‒F (see also Fig. 9)." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF0F660FFFCA2200FF55F9FCFCCB876C" pageId="27" pageNumber="428" tableUuid="DF0F660FFFCA2200FF55F9FCFCCB876C">Tables 6</tableCitation>
, 
<tableCitation box="[962,977,1348,1374]" captionStart="TABLE 8" captionStartId="17.[151,239,151,175]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="TABLE 8. Mean and standard deviation values of nine “shortsong” characters measured for Megascops atricapilla-M. watsonii individuals belonging to clades A‒F." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF0F660FFFD5221FFF55FF73FD8581EC" pageId="27" pageNumber="428" tableUuid="DF0F660FFFD5221FFF55FF73FD8581EC">8</tableCitation>
, and 10).
</paragraph>
